<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>1150</anchor>  <taxon>Idea</taxon> <addr>axt-004D</addr>  <route>axt-004D.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>12</month> <day>6</day></date> <authors><author><link href="ayberkt.xml" type="local">Ayberk Tosun</link></author> <contributor><link href="todd-wilson.xml" type="local">J. Todd Wilson</link></contributor></authors> <title>Maxsets in a predicative setting</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>  In impredicative locale theory, the notion of a <link href="axt-003I.xml" type="local" title="Maxset">maxset</link> is defined
  as:
</p><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>1</crumb></trail> <anchor>1151</anchor>  <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>axt-003I</addr>  <route>axt-003I.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>8</day></date> <authors><author><link href="todd-wilson.xml" type="local">J. Todd Wilson</link></author> </authors> <title>Maxset</title> <meta name="source"><b>Paragraph 13.2</b> (p. 66) of <link href="wilson-thesis.xml" type="local" title="The Assembly Tower and Some Categorical and Algebraic Aspects of Frame Theory">Wilson's thesis</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>  Let <tex>L</tex> be a <link href="axt-003J.xml" type="local" title="Frame">frame</link>. A subset <tex>M  \subseteq  L</tex> is called a
  <b>maxset</b> if,
  <ol>    <li>it is closed under arbitrary meets, and</li>    <li>      it is an exponential ideal i.e.
      <tex>\forall  x  \in  L. \  \forall  m  \in  M. \  (x  \Rightarrow  m)  \in  M</tex>.
    </li>  </ol></p></mainmatter> </tree><p>  It is a standard fact of locale theory that there is a correspondence
  between the set of nuclei on and the class of maxsets of any frame.
